    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Small, stemless perennial emerging from a bulb buried deep underground and with sour, acidic sap. Leaves form a small rosette and each is divided into three broadly heart-shaped leaflets that bear fine hairs along their margins and are purple beneath. Flowers large and funnel-shaped with five broad petals, furl at night and open when exposed to sun. Flowers usually purple (rarely pink, yellow or white) always with a yellow tube.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10010",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Plants about 20 cm in diameter and only 6-7 cm tall.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10011",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa. Widely introduced including to California, Azores, Canary Islands, Spain, Portugal, Italy, India, Tasmania, Morocco, Tristan da Cunha.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namaqualand to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10012",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Extremely common both along the coast and further inland across the winter rainfall regions of South Africa, often forming dense patches. Common in domestic lawns where they tolerate mowing due to their low growth form and are sometimes regarded as a weed, although they make an attractive display. Proliferate readily and have been accidentally introduced to many parts of the world with suitable climates.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10013",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10014",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers May to September. Propagates largely by producing smaller bulbils around the parent, resulting in dense group of plants occurring close together. Seed capsules small and contain many tiny seeds. Capsules burst when mature expelling the seeds in all directions.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10015",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This is a large and complex genus of over 500 species, including over 100 in the fynbos region, making species level identifications sometimes challenging. Among the many similar species <i>O. obtusa</i> is usually pink with darker veins and <i>O. eckloniana</i> is taller. See guides referred to for images of many other species.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10016",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Manning, J (2007). Field Guide to Fynbos. Cape Town: Random House Struik. (p. 216).<br><br>Manning, J & Goldblatt, P (2000). South African Wild Flower Guide 7: West Coast. Botanical Society of South Africa (p. 156).<br><br>Zietsman, J, Dreyer, LL & Van Vuuren, BJ (2009). Genetic differentiation in <i>Oxalis</i> (Oxalidaceae): a tale of rarity and abundance in the Cape Floristic Region. <i>South African Journal of Botany</i>, 75(1), 27-33.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10017",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
